Introduction

In this tutorial, I will take you through the entire data science pipeline starting from data curation, parsing, and management, exploratory data analysis, and hypothesis testing and machine learning to provide analysis. Throughout this, we will be trying to see if social interaction, influence, and popularity of players and teams have an affect on NBA in terms of game stats and wins.

Read Dataset and Tidy

The first step will be to include all packages that are necessary and read the multiple datasets that we need. After doing this, we will need to tidy the data set and get rid of any missing data and change names as needed. In order to get a precise and accurate analysis, this step is very important. In this tutorial, we will use multiple datasets provided from kaggle.com under the name of social power nba.

As you can see from the datasets, playerStats consists of players from the nba and their respective stats for the 2016-2017 season. It also includes stats for social media and page views. The teamAttendance dataset contains attendance stats for all the teams in the nba including other stats like wins.

Analyzing the data

Does twitter interaction impact indivual player stats and performance?

#plot stats against twitter combined stats

#points
ggplot(data = playerStats, aes(x = twitterCombined, y = POINTS) )+
  geom_point(color = "blue") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Points vs Twitter Interaction") +
  xlab("Twitter Interaction") + ylab("Points")

#assists

ggplot(data = playerStats, aes(x = twitterCombined, y = AST) )+
  geom_point(color = "green") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Assists vs Twitter Interaction") +
  xlab("Twitter Interaction") + ylab("Assists")

#rebounds
ggplot(data = playerStats, aes(x = twitterCombined, y = TRB) )+
  geom_point(color = "orange") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Rebounds vs Twitter Interaction") +
  xlab("Twitter Interaction") + ylab("Rebounds")

As you can see here, twitter stats plotted against player stats give us a positive correlation between the two. For points, assists, and rebounds, there seems to a connection which says that the more a player interacts on twitter, the better their offensive stats are. As you can see from the graphs, there are many outliers that possiblly skew the data. Also since there are many players that do not use social media that much, it can be hard to use this data as fact. Next we will compare offensive and defensive rating with twitter interaction. These ratings may give us a better understanding of how twitter interaction can affect how well an NBA player does.

#offensive and defensive ratings plotted against twitter interaction. 

#offensive
ggplot(data = playerStats, aes(x = twitterCombined, y = ORPM) )+
  geom_point(color = "blue") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Offensive Rating vs Twitter Interaction") +
  xlab("Twitter Interaction") + ylab("Offensive Rating")

#defensive
ggplot(data = playerStats, aes(x = twitterCombined, y = DRPM) )+
  geom_point(color = "green") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Defensive Rating vs Twitter Interaction") +
  xlab("Twitter Interaction") + ylab("Defensive Rating")

As you can see from these graphs, the correlation between Offensive rating and twitter interaction is similar to the correlation of the offensive stats that I tested. Although this is similar to before, the defensive rating tells us a different story. As you can see from the graph, twitter interaction has almost no effect on the defensive rating of an NBA player. From this alone, we can possibly bring up that maybe twitter interaction only has an affect on offensive play and not defensive but due to the outliers, we cannot use this for fact.

Removing players with

We now want to see what if the outliers really have that big of an impact on the visual data than we think. To do this, I removed any players with more than 2000 retweets and likes (twitter interaction) and 2000 page views (fan interaction). This will give us a better understanding of how players are impacted by these kinds of interactions and if the very popular players really have an impact on how this data is represented.

playerStats2 <- subset(playerStats, twitterCombined < 2000, PAGEVIEWS < 2000)

ggplot(data = playerStats2, aes(x = twitterCombined, y = ORPM) )+
  geom_point(color = "green") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Offensive Rating vs Fan Interaction") +
  xlab("Twitter Interaction") + ylab("Defensive Rating")

ggplot(data = playerStats2, aes(x = twitterCombined, y = DRPM) )+
  geom_point(color = "green") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Defensive Rating vs Fan Interaction") +
  xlab("Twitter Interaction") + ylab("Defensive Rating")

ggplot(data = playerStats2, aes(x = PAGEVIEWS, y = ORPM) )+
  geom_point(color = "green") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Oefensive Rating vs Fan Interaction") +
  xlab("Fan Interaction") + ylab("Defensive Rating")

ggplot(data = playerStats2, aes(x = PAGEVIEWS, y = DRPM) )+
  geom_point(color = "green") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Defensive Rating vs Fan Interaction") +
  xlab("Fan Interaction") + ylab("Defensive Rating")

Looking at these results, we can say that the correlation that we see between interaction of players and fans against NBA players stats and how well they play is not skewed greatly by the players who are very popular or use twitter a lot. With this we can confirm the accusations made earlier in the tutorial in terms of how interaction impacts player performance.

Now that we know this, lets calculate some statistics for fun.

What position in basketball is the is the most social and the most popular to fans?

We will now compare the different positions in basketball and see which have the most twitter interaction and which have the most fan interaction.

#lets us see the median and quartile values so we can create a subset.
summary(playerStats$t)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##     0.0    15.5    40.0   329.3   120.1 15170.0       3
playerStats3rdQuartile <- subset(playerStats, twitterCombined < 120.1, PAGEVIEWS < 642.8)


##twitter interaction
ggplot(data = playerStats3rdQuartile, aes(x=POSITION, y=twitterCombined)) + 
 geom_boxplot()+ ggtitle("Comparing positions with twitter interaction") +
  xlab("Positions") + ylab("Twitter Interaction")+ stat_summary(fun.y=median, colour="darkred", geom="point", hape=18, size=3,show_legend = FALSE)+ stat_summary(fun.y=median, colour="red", geom="text", show_legend = FALSE, 
               vjust=-0.7, aes( label=round(..y.., digits=1)))

ggplot(data = playerStats3rdQuartile, aes(x=POSITION, y=PAGEVIEWS)) + 
 geom_boxplot()+ ggtitle("Comparing positions with fan interaction") +
  xlab("Positions") + ylab("Fan Interaction")+ stat_summary(fun.y=median, colour="darkred", geom="point", hape=18, size=3,show_legend = FALSE)+ stat_summary(fun.y=median, colour="red", geom="text", show_legend = FALSE, 
               vjust=-0.7, aes( label=round(..y.., digits=1)))

For this I used data that was contained in the 3rd quartile and below for the dataset. I did this because the data beyond that point are is so much greater than the data in the third quartile and below that it did not allow us to see the graph properly and skews the box plot when included. From plotting box plots of each position we learn some interesting information. First we see that the highest when looking at twitter interaction, centers are the most active. I say this because they have the highest median out of all positions for this statistic. Second, I can conclude that the position that has the most fan interaction is center as well. I come to this conclusion the same way as I did with twitter interaction, which is looking at the median. Obviously if I include the last quartile, this data will change but I wanted to see the results for 75% of the data accurately rather than having the top 25% impact the rest of the data so greatly.

Does fan attendance impact team play?

Now that we have done all these calculation, we have a pretty good understanding of how player and fan social interaction can affect the play and stats of NBA players, lets look at teams. In the followning part of the tutorial, we will look at how fan attendance impacts how well a team performs. To do this, we will look at the team ELO compared to avg attendance and attendance percentage. Team ELO was a statistic given by the kaggle dataset which calculates the relative skill and performance of the team. We will use this to compare team performances and see if there really is a connection between the two variables.

ggplot(data = teamAttendance, aes(x = ELO, y = AVG) )+
  geom_point(color = "blue") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Avg attendance vs Team Elo") +
  xlab("Average Attendance") + ylab("Team Elo")+geom_text(aes(label=TEAM),hjust=0, vjust=0)

ggplot(data = teamAttendance, aes(x = ELO, y = PCT) )+
  geom_point(color = "green") + geom_smooth(method='lm', color = "red") + ggtitle("Percent Attendance vs Team Elo") +
  xlab("Attendance Percent") + ylab("Team Elo")+geom_text(aes(label=TEAM),hjust=0, vjust=0)

As we can see from this, there is a sight positive correlation between attendance percentage/average and team Elo. If we look, many teams with good records like Warriors, Spurs and the Rockets also have a high attendance rate which makes sense. There are also teams like Mavericks, Kings, and Lakers who are not that good record wise but still have high attendance. From this I say that there is definitely a weak correlation between the two variables but I believe attendance is more connected to location of the team rather than how well it does.

Linear Regression Model

After analyzing data, the next thing we could do is test our result. We will make a linear regression model to see how twitter and interaction would change depending on the following variables: Offensive Rating and Defensive Rating. We want to see if we were correct with assumptions in saying that effect of offensive and defensive rating are statistically significant. We will also create a linear model to see if team ELO would change depending on the following variables: Average Team Attendance and Attendance Percentage. We want to see if were correct in saying that there is a weak correlation between attendance and ELO and therefore not statistically significant.

In [16]:

twitterRes<-lm(twitterCombined~ORPM + DRPM, data = playerStats)

wikiRes <- lm(PAGEVIEWS~ ORPM + DRPM, data = playerStats)

teamRes<-lm(ELO~AVG, data = teamAttendance)
teamRes<-lm(ELO~PCT, data = teamAttendance)


summary(twitterRes)

Conclusion

As we can see from the statistics, there are statistics that are statistically significant. For twitter interactions by players, just as we predicted, offensive rating is statistically significant while defensive rating is not. This assumption also holds true for fan interaction, which tells us that fan and player twitter interactin does have an impact on offensive rating. Along with this, we also did a linear model for attendance and we saw that just as we predicted from the plots, there is a statistically significant connection between the variables. Overall, we conclude offensive play for an NBA player can be affected by social interaction whether fan or player and that attendance does not impact Team Elo or how well a team plays and performs.
